        <textarea id="contact-pubkey" rows="3" placeholder="Paste their public key (starts with eyJ...)"></textarea>
      </div>
      <button class="btn btn-primary" onclick="deriveShared()">🤝 Derive Shared Encryption Key</button>
      <div id="shared-ok" class="alert a-ok hidden" style="margin-top:0.8rem;">
        <span>✅ Shared secret derived successfully. You can now use the <strong>Encrypt</strong> and <strong>Decrypt</strong> tabs with this shared key. This key was never transmitted — it was computed locally from your private key and their public key.</span>
      </div>
      <div id="shared-err" class="alert a-err hidden"><span id="shared-err-msg"></span></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">
    <div class="card-title"><span class="dot"></span>How E2EE works — the ECDH protocol</div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-body"><strong>Key generation</strong><span>You and your contact each generate an ECDH key pair independently.</span></div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-body"><strong>Public key exchange</strong><span>You exchange public keys over any channel (email, chat — even a postcard). Public keys cannot decrypt messages.</span></div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-body"><strong>Shared secret</strong><span>Both parties derive the same shared secret from their own private key + the other's public key. This is the ECDH magic — no secret was ever transmitted.</span></div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="step-num">4</div><div class="step-body"><strong>E2EE encryption</strong><span>Messages are encrypted with the shared secret. Only the two key holders can decrypt — not us, not your email provider, not anyone intercepting traffic.</span></div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

